y, loyal addresses acknowledged the existence of a ‘political public’ but did so in a way which fundamentally conceded the legitimacy of the social and political hierarchy. They constituted a political form perfectly suited to a fundamentally unequal society in which political life continued to be centered on the monarchy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPublic opinionzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aPublic opinionzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 4aPolitical Studies 2020. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAddress.  aEngland.  aLoyalty.  aOath.  aPetition.  aPolitics.  aReligion.  amemory.  aopinion.  apublic.1 aVallance, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packagez978311128249740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611790840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526117908423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526117908/original  a978-3-11-128249-7  Manchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packageb2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles